  "Though creating a simple <code>Counter</code> app is <span class=\"font-black tracking-wider\" style=\"color:var(--blue)\">cool</span> and gives us a gentle introduction to <code>useState</code>, it's not <em metastring=\"\">super</em> practical. Let's look at some other use cases that'll give us more insight into how we can leverage <code>useState</code> in more scenarios.": "",
  "It's important to note that when you pass a value to <code>useState</code>'s updater function, whatever value you pass will always <strong metastring=\"\">replace</strong> the current piece of state.": "",
  "Instead of replacing the object, you most likely want to <strong metastring=\"\">merge</strong> the new value with the existing state object. To do that, we can use JavaScript's spread operator to spread all of the existing key/value pairs onto a new object, then pass that new object to the updater function.": "",
  "At this point our app is progressing <del metastring=\"\">slowly</del> nicely. Unfortunately, it still doesn't resemble much of a todo <em metastring=\"\">list</em>.": "",
  "What if instead of having each <code>Todo</code> component manage its own state, we <span class=\"font-bold relative m-px\" style=\"bottom:0px\">l</span><span class=\"font-bold relative m-px\" style=\"bottom:1px\">i</span><span class=\"font-bold relative m-px\" style=\"bottom:2px\">f</span><span class=\"font-bold relative m-px\" style=\"bottom:3px\">t</span> that state up to the parent <code>TodoList</code> component?": "",
  "This would solve all of our problems. <code>TodoList</code> would <em metastring=\"\">own</em> (and manage) the state of each todo item and then we can pass data down to components that need it via props.": "",
  "The only gotcha is how you update that state. Often times when lifting state up, you decouple <em metastring=\"\">where</em> the state lives from the event handlers that update that state.": "",
  "So first, let's <span class=\"font-bold relative m-px\" style=\"bottom:0px\">l</span><span class=\"font-bold relative m-px\" style=\"bottom:1px\">i</span><span class=\"font-bold relative m-px\" style=\"bottom:2px\">f</span><span class=\"font-bold relative m-px\" style=\"bottom:3px\">t</span> our <span class=\"ch-section-link\" data-active=\"false\">todo state</span> up to a new <code>TodoList</code> component and then pass it down via a prop to the <span class=\"ch-section-link\" data-active=\"false\">Todo</span> component.": "",
  "First, we'll remove the local <code>todo</code> state and accept it as a <span class=\"ch-section-link\" data-active=\"false\">prop</span> since it now lives inside of the parent <span class=\"ch-section-link\" data-active=\"false\"><code>TodoList</code></span> component.": "",
  "Next, we'll update our event handlers to use our new <code>handleUpdateTodo</code> prop that we also passed down from the parent <span class=\"ch-section-link\" data-active=\"false\"><code>TodoList</code></span> component.": "",
  "Notice that <code>handleUpdateTodo</code> has an <span class=\"ch-section-link\" data-active=\"false\"><code>updatedTodo</code></span> parameter. This is how we get data from where the event handlers live, in a child component, back up to where the state lives, in the parent component.": "",
  "It doesn't matter <em metastring=\"\">where</em> <code>handleUpdateTodo</code> is called, it just matters that when it's called, it receives this <code>updatedTodo</code> argument.": "",
  "So now inside of the child <code>Todo</code> component, we need to make sure when we invoke <span class=\"ch-section-link\" data-active=\"false\">handleUpdateTodo</span>, we pass it the updated todo item.": "",
  "At this point our app is in better shape than it was before, but it's still not a todo <strong metastring=\"\">list</strong>. Let's fix that.": "",
  "We'll do the same thing here by updating the state in our <code>TodoList</code> component to be an <em metastring=\"\">array</em> of todo objects, rather than just a single todo object.": "",
  "Similar to objects, whenever you want to update an array that's on state, you need to pass the updater function a <strong metastring=\"\">new</strong> array which will replace the current array.": "",
